SIMPLE: flutist
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flutist
<hw>Flut"ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>fl⟦ucir⟧tiste</ets>.]</ety> <def>A performer on the flute; a
flautist.</def> <rj><au>Busby.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 576 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move with quick vibrations or undulations;
<as>as, a sail <ex>flutters</ex> in the wind; a <ex>fluttering</ex>
fan.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To move about briskly, irregularly, or with great
bustle and show, without much result.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> No rag, no scrap, of all the beau, or wit,⟦br⟧
That once so <qex>fluttered</qex>, and that once so writ.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be in agitation; to move irregularly; to
fluctuate; to be uncertainty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Long we <qex>fluttered</qex> on the wings of doubtful
success.</q> <rj><qau>Howell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> His thoughts are very <qex>fluttering</qex> and wandering.</q>
<rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flutter</ent>⟦br⟧
